<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ts-strict-isolated">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>sdlc-ai</group>
    <domain>sdlc-ai</domain>
    <summary>Every tsconfig.json must enable strict, noUncheckedIndexedAccess, exactOptionalPropertyTypes; libraries also need isolatedDeclarations + composite + references to catch LLM type errors.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>typescript</tag>
      <tag>strict-mode</tag>
      <tag>isolated-declarations</tag>
      <tag>project-references</tag>
      <tag>monorepo</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>lang</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-30</created>
    <languages>
      <language>typescript</language>
    </languages>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>TypeScript Strict + isolatedDeclarations + Project References</title>
    <summary>Every tsconfig.json in a TypeScript workspace must enable "strict": true, "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true, "exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true, and (for libraries / shared packages) "isolatedDeclarations": true plus "composite": true with references to its dependency packages. This raises compile-time precision so that AI-generated code surfaces type errors instead of runtime bugs, and lets fast emitters (Biome, oxc, swc) produce .d.ts without invoking tsc for inference.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>LLM-written code statistically prefers permissive shapes (any, untyped index access, optional fields it never sets). Strict mode + noUncheckedIndexedAccess makes those tells into compile errors the agent must fix before the change is accepted; exactOptionalPropertyTypes distinguishes "absent" from "explicitly undefined" so partial-update bugs cannot hide. isolatedDeclarations constrains exported APIs to be expressible without inference, which keeps the public surface stable and unlocks 10–50x faster declaration emission via non-tsc tools — sub-second feedback that an agentic edit loop relies on. Project references make package builds incremental and parallel.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any monorepo with two or more packages.</item>
        <item>Any published library, regardless of size.</item>
        <item>Any application codebase larger than ~10k lines or with multiple AI agents editing concurrently.</item>
        <item>Greenfield TS projects, default-on.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Throwaway single-file scripts, scratch Bun/Deno snippets, REPL experiments — strictness overhead outweighs the value at this size.</item>
        <item>Application entrypoints (apps, not libs) — keep strict and noUncheckedIndexedAccess on, but skip isolatedDeclarations since apps emit no .d.ts.</item>
        <item>Codebases mid-migration where flipping flags would block trunk for weeks — adopt incrementally with // @ts-expect-error budgets.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="required-flag-set">
      <p>The minimal strict configuration is a tight set: strict is the umbrella, plus three extras that catch the failure modes LLMs most often introduce, plus isolatedDeclarations for libraries.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every tsconfig.json sets compilerOptions.strict: true, noUncheckedIndexedAccess: true, exactOptionalPropertyTypes: true. Library tsconfigs additionally set isolatedDeclarations: true and composite: true.</statement>
        <rationale>strict enables noImplicitAny, strictNullChecks, strictFunctionTypes, etc. — the baseline. noUncheckedIndexedAccess forces narrowing on arr[i] and obj[key], the #1 LLM blind spot. exactOptionalPropertyTypes separates "missing key" from "key set to undefined", killing partial-update bugs. isolatedDeclarations requires explicit return types on every export so non-tsc tools can emit .d.ts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Base config with all required flags">
        <code lang="jsonc"><![CDATA[
// tsconfig.base.json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": true,
    "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true,
    "exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true,
    "noImplicitOverride": true,
    "module": "NodeNext",
    "moduleResolution": "NodeNext",
    "target": "ES2023"
  }
}
        ]]></code>
        <note>One base config; per-package configs extend this and add composite / isolatedDeclarations if they are libraries.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Permissive config that hides LLM errors">
        <code lang="jsonc"><![CDATA[
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": false,
    "noImplicitAny": false,
    "skipLibCheck": true
  }
}
        ]]></code>
        <note>Implicit any everywhere; unchecked array access never narrows; LLM diffs compile but crash at runtime.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Disabling strict for one file via // @ts-nocheck instead of fixing the type error.</description>
        <reason>The escape hatch turns an entire file into untyped JS. Use // @ts-expect-error: &lt;ticket&gt; on the single line, or fix the type properly. Agents will copy @ts-nocheck patterns once they see one example.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="project-references">
      <p>Project references split a TypeScript workspace into independently buildable units. Each library declares composite: true and lists its dependents under references. Builds use tsc --build (or per-package tsc -b); editors get faster cross-package navigation because each package consumes its dependency's .d.ts, not its source.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every library package's tsconfig sets composite: true and lists every internal dependency under references: [{ path: "../&lt;dep&gt;" }]. Application packages add references to all libraries they import. Run tsc --build from the root; never tsc -p per package in CI.</statement>
        <rationale>Without composite, declaration emit is incremental-incompatible and editor navigation re-checks across boundaries. With it, each package builds once, downstream packages reuse .d.ts, total CI time drops 3–10x on large monorepos. tsc --build orchestrates the dependency graph; ad-hoc per-package builds skip the graph and rebuild redundantly.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Library tsconfig with composite and references">
        <code lang="jsonc"><![CDATA[
// packages/core/tsconfig.json
{
  "extends": "../../tsconfig.base.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    "composite": true,
    "isolatedDeclarations": true,
    "declaration": true,
    "declarationMap": true,
    "outDir": "dist",
    "rootDir": "src"
  },
  "include": ["src"],
  "references": [{ "path": "../shared" }]
}
        ]]></code>
        <note>core depends on shared; tsc --build will build shared first, emit .d.ts, then build core against those .d.ts.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Importing across packages by relative path (../../shared/src/foo.ts) instead of by package name with a references entry.</description>
        <reason>Bypasses the project reference graph — tsc cannot determine build order, editors cannot do cross-package go-to-definition. Treat each package as an opaque module identifiable by its package.json name.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/tsconfig.base.json" purpose="Shared base with all required strict flags; packages extend this."/>
      <template path="templates/tsconfig.lib.json" purpose="Library tsconfig with composite + isolatedDeclarations + references example."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.typescriptlang.org/tsconfig/strict.html"/>
      <link href="https://www.typescriptlang.org/tsconfig/noUncheckedIndexedAccess.html"/>
      <link href="https://www.typescriptlang.org/tsconfig/isolatedDeclarations.html"/>
      <link href="https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/project-references.html"/>
      <link href="https://moonrepo.dev/docs/guides/javascript/typescript-project-refs"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
